text.paragraph:
Because escitalopram is extensively metabolized, excretion of unchanged drug in urine is a minor route of elimination. Until adequate numbers of patients with severe renal impairment have been evaluated during chronic treatment with escitalopram, however, it should be used with caution in such patients [see 
                                 Dosage and Administration (2.3)

                           ].

In two pharmacokinetic studies, escitalopram half-life was increased by approximately 50% in elderly subjects as compared to young subjects and Cmax was unchanged [see Clinical Pharmacology (12.3)
                           ]. 10 mg/day is the recommended dose for elderly patients [see Dosage and Administration (2.3)
                           ].
